- Directionality: Ensure the subject is the driver and the object is the affected phenomenon. Avoid embedding the change word ("decrease/increase") in the object when the relation already encodes direction.
  - Instead of "X CAUSES decrease in Y", prefer "X DECREASES Y".
- Semantic precision: Replace nominalized "decrease in spread of fire" / "decrease in size of burnt areas" with the underlying phenomena "spread of fire" / "size of burnt areas" and use DECREASES if the text supports a reduction.

2) Completeness
- Entity normalization will recover missing links: normalize repeated concepts to a single canonical span (e.g., "herbaceous standing crop" always as that token sequence). This avoids treating "decrease in herbaceous standing crop" as a distinct entity from "herbaceous standing crop".
- Check for implied causal chains that should be represented explicitly if present in the text. For example, if the text states shortening fallow period -> decreased herbaceous fuel -> reduced fire spread/area, record both links with appropriate relations:
